# Authoring AGENTS.md

The agent guide (`AGENTS.md`) is the one doc loaded every session. Follow the [Documentation Standard](doc-standard.md) for how to write; this doc adds what is specific to the guide.

<!-- awf:section layout -->
## Layout

The guide renders a fixed sequence of sections:

1. **Working with awf**: awf-given; how the config tree renders the project.
2. **You and this project**: adopter-authored; the agent's standing responsibility.
3. **Identity**: adopter-authored; what the project is.
4. **Invariants**: adopter-authored; the hard rules every change respects.
5. **Workflow**: awf-given; entry-skill triggers only, derived from the catalog.
6. **Working memory**: awf-given; the resume trigger, ground-rule one-liners, and the canonical-protocol pointer only.
7. **Commands**: adopter data; the handful of commands an agent runs.
8. **Document map**: awf-given; the index into the docs, generated from the enabled set.

Override an adopter-authored section with a convention part at `.awf/parts/agents-doc/<section>.md`, or supply `data` (invariants, commands) in `.awf/agents-doc.yaml`.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section content -->
## Content

- **Identity**: one dense paragraph covering what the project is, its stack and module path, its maturity, and who it serves. No history.
- **You and this project**: two or three sentences on the agent's ownership stance, the project's long-term health, not just the task.
- **Invariants**: only the cross-cutting hard rules, one terse imperative line each, with the owning ADR in parentheses where one exists. A rule belongs here iff it is *not scoped to a single subsystem's files*: it constrains a whole cross-cutting surface (every commit's process, all code, all rendered output, the toolchain's own preconditions). A path- or subsystem-specific invariant stays out of the guide, in its owning ADR. The mechanism always lives in that ADR.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section rules -->
## Rules

The guide is loaded every session, so it is held to an extra-terse bar; it pays its word cost on every task. The workflow section names entry skills and their triggers, never procedure: the chain routes itself through skill handoffs, and chain rules live in the workflow doc. The working-memory protocol has one canonical home in the workflow doc's working-memory section; the guide carries the resume trigger and pointers only. State each invariant as a one-line imperative and let its ADR carry the detail. Do not mirror the ADR ledger into the Invariants section: a rule earns a line only when it applies no matter which files a change touches. Reach path-specific orientation on demand through concise `awf context <paths>` and request the complete authority packet with `awf context --full <paths>`; concise output reports omitted topic-wide claims rather than silently weakening them. Treat request paths, effective paths, and their primary classifications as navigation facts, not authority by themselves. Use `awf topic <domain>/<topic> --coverage` for the separate domain/topic selectors and their both-must-match evidence. A configured `currentState.maxClaimsPerTopic` note is advisory and never truncates either projection. The managed runner is a pure `./awf` wrapper forwarding every CLI verb verbatim; project verbs live in the adopter's own runner. Use the generated ADR status index where the project configures domains, or the ADR index otherwise. `--full --uncovered` is invalid because coverage gaps are not an authority projection. Push anything else not every-session-critical into a doc reached through the document map.
<!-- awf:end -->
